## Why This Is Asked

This question tests non-blocking IPC design under kernel constraints, focusing on memory ordering, CAS-based synchronization, wraparound handling, and backpressure mechanisms.

## Key Concepts

- **Non-blocking SPSC ring design**: Single-producer, single-consumer architecture eliminates locking overhead
- **Atomic operations and memory barriers**: Ensure proper ordering of loads and stores without locks
- **Cacheline padding**: Align head/tail indices to separate cache lines, preventing false sharing between CPU cores
- **Wraparound logic**: Use modulo arithmetic or bit-masking (when N is a power of 2) to handle circular buffer indexing
- **Overflow signaling**: Track the distance between head and tail to detect full/empty conditions; use separate flags or sequence numbers for accurate state detection
- **Burst workload testing**: Verify no data loss, no misordering, and no stalls under high-throughput scenarios

## Memory Layout

```c
typedef struct { int data; uint64_t seq; } item_t;

typedef struct {
    _Atomic uint64_t head L1_CACHE_LINE_ALIGNED;
    _Atomic uint64_t tail L1_CACHE_LINE_ALIGNED;
    char pad1[L1_CACHE_LINE_SIZE - sizeof(_Atomic uint64_t)];
    item_t buf[N];
    char pad2[L1_CACHE_LINE_SIZE];  // Tail padding to prevent write-through
} ring_buffer_t;
```

## Enqueue (Producer)

```c
bool enqueue(ring_buffer_t* rb, item_t* item) {
    uint64_t head = atomic_load_explicit(&rb->head, memory_order_acquire);
    uint64_t next_head = (head + 1) & (N - 1);  // Power-of-2 wraparound

    if (next_head == atomic_load_explicit(&rb->tail, memory_order_acquire)) {
        return false;  // Buffer full (one slot reserved)
    }

    rb->buf[head] = *item;
    atomic_store_explicit(&rb->head, next_head, memory_order_release);
    return true;
}
```

## Dequeue (Consumer)

```c
bool dequeue(ring_buffer_t* rb, item_t* item) {
    uint64_t tail = atomic_load_explicit(&rb->tail, memory_order_acquire);
    uint64_t head = atomic_load_explicit(&rb->head, memory_order_acquire);

    if (tail == head) {
        return false;  // Buffer empty
    }

    *item = rb->buf[tail];
    uint64_t next_tail = (tail + 1) & (N - 1);
    atomic_store_explicit(&rb->tail, next_tail, memory_order_release);
    return true;
}
```

## Test Plan

| Test Case | Method | Pass Criteria |
|-----------|--------|---------------|
| **Data loss detection** | Inject known sequence numbers, compare enqueued vs. dequeued count | Zero missing sequence numbers |
| **Misordering detection** | Tag each item with monotonic sequence ID, verify strictly increasing order on dequeue | Sequence IDs monotonically increase |
| **Burst traffic** | Enqueue N items rapidly, then dequeue all; repeat with varying N | All items recovered, correct order |
| **Concurrent stress** | Run producer/consumer threads on separate cores, measure throughput | No stalls, no corruption |
| **Wraparound stress** | Fill buffer, drain, repeat N > capacity times | No indexing errors after multiple wraparounds |
| **Overflow handling** | Attempt enqueue when full, verify rejection | Returns false, no corruption |
| **Empty buffer** | Attempt dequeue when empty, verify rejection | Returns false, no corruption |

