questions.answer:
In a COW fork, parent and child initially share all physical pages marked as read-only. On a write fault to a shared page: (1) Check the reference count; if greater than 1, allocate a new page, copy the old content, decrement the reference count, map the new page with write permissions for the faulting process, and flush the TLB for that virtual address. (2) If the reference count equals 1 (only the current process references the page), simply enable write permissions. C-like pseudocode:

```c
int cow_fault_handler(vaddr_t addr) {
    pte_t *pte = get_pte(current->pgd, addr);
    page_t *page = pte->page;

    if (atomic_dec_and_test(&page->refcount)) {
        pte_set_writable(pte);
        tlb_flush_vaddr(addr);
        return 0;
    }

    page_t *newpage = alloc_page();
    memcpy(newpage->data, page->data, PAGE_SIZE);
    atomic_inc(&newpage->refcount);

    pte->page = newpage;
    pte_set_writable(pte);
    tlb_flush_vaddr(addr);
    return 0;
}
```

Testing: (1) Fork and verify parent and child see the same data initially, (2) Have each modify their copy and verify isolation, (3) Check that reference counts drop correctly on unmap, (4) Stress test with many concurrent forks to catch race conditions.

