- Race conditions during concurrent faults on the same page
- Minimal fault handler design and synchronization primitives

## Code Example

```c
// Per-page lock structure
typedef struct {
    spinlock_t lock;
    int ref_count;
} COWPage;

// Global table mapping physical frames to COW metadata
COWPage *cow_table[MAX_FRAMES];

void handle_write_fault(Process *p, VirtAddr va) {
    PageTableEntry *pte = walk_page_table(p->pgd, va);

    if (!pte || !(pte->flags & COW_BIT))
        return; // Not a COW page fault

    PhysAddr frame = pte->frame;
    COWPage *cow = cow_table[frame];

    spin_lock(&cow->lock);

    // Double-check after acquiring lock
    if (cow->ref_count > 1) {
        // Allocate new frame
        PhysAddr new_frame = allocate_frame();

        // Copy content
        memcpy(phys_to_virt(new_frame), phys_to_virt(frame), PAGE_SIZE);

        // Decrement original reference count
        cow->ref_count--;

        // Update current process page table
        pte->frame = new_frame;
        pte->flags = (pte->flags & ~COW_BIT) | WRITABLE_BIT;

        // Add new frame to COW table with ref_count = 1
        cow_table[new_frame] = cow;
        cow_table[new_frame]->ref_count = 1;
    } else {
        // Last reference - just make writable
        pte->flags = (pte->flags & ~COW_BIT) | WRITABLE_BIT;
    }

    spin_unlock(&cow->lock);
}
```

## Race Handling

Using per-page locks ensures that only one process can handle the fault for a given physical page at a time. The double-check pattern (checking ref_count before and after acquiring the lock) prevents redundant duplications. CAS (Compare-And-Swap) can also be used to atomically decrement the reference count and allocate a new page in a single operation.

