## Multi-Queue I/O Scheduler Design

### Core Design
This scheduler organizes I/O requests into per-NUMA-node, per-process queues. Each NUMA node maintains a separate queue for every process, allowing both NUMA locality and process-level fairness.

**Key components:**
- **Per-NUMA queues**: I/Os go to the NUMA node where the target NVMe device is located
- **Per-process sub-queues**: Within each NUMA node, separate queues track each process's requests
- **Global deadline wheel**: Orders I/Os by deadline across all NUMA partitions
- **Adaptive throttling**: Monitors queue depth and latency (p50, p99) to dynamically adjust batch sizes

### End-to-End Path

1. **Submission**: Process calls `submit_io()`, which determines the target NUMA node from device topology
2. **Enqueue**: I/O is added to the per-process queue within that NUMA node using lock-free CAS (compare-and-swap)
3. **Wakeup**: The NUMA kernel thread wakes and scans for expired deadlines
4. **Batching**: I/Os with imminent or exceeded deadlines are grouped into batches
5. **Submission**: Batched I/Os are sent to the NVMe device via PCIe DMA
6. **Completion**: Interrupt fires on the owning NUMA node; I/O is marked complete
7. **Throttling**: Latency tracking updates; if p99 exceeds SLA, throttling adjusts

### Race Conditions

| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| Enqueue vs dispatch on same queue | CAS with proper memory barriers |
| Multiple NVMe completions updating stats | Atomic increments or per-CPU counters |
| NUMA migration during I/O | Pin I/O to originating NUMA node until completion |
| Deadline wheel rebalancing | Use RCU for safe traversal |

### Code Sketch

```c
#define MAX_NODES 64
#define MAX_PROCS 4096

typedef struct io_item {
    uint64_t    id;
    uint64_t    deadline;
    uint32_t    flags;
    void        *next;
} io_item;

typedef struct percpu_queue {
    io_item     *head;
    io_item     *tail;
    uint32_t    count;
} percpu_queue;

typedef struct numa_proc_queue {
    percpu_queue    queues[MAX_PROCS];
    uint64_t        last_dispatch[MAX_PROCS];
    spinlock_t      lock;
} numa_proc_queue;

typedef struct scheduler {
    numa_proc_queue node_queues[MAX_NODES];
    uint64_t        throttle_threshold;
    uint32_t        batch_size;
} scheduler;

// Lock-free enqueue
int enqueue_io(scheduler *sched, int numa_node, int proc_id, io_item *it) {
    percpu_queue *q = &sched->node_queues[numa_node].queues[proc_id];

    it->next = NULL;

    for (;;) {
        io_item *prev = atomic_load_explicit(&q->tail, memory_order_relaxed);
        it->next = prev;
        if (atomic_compare_exchange_weak_explicit(
            &q->tail, &prev, it,
            memory_order_release, memory_order_relaxed)) {
            atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&q->count, 1, memory_order_relaxed);
            return 1;
        }
    }
}

// Dispatch - earliest deadline with fairness
io_item* dispatch_next(scheduler *sched) {
    uint64_t earliest = UINT64_MAX;
    io_item *best = NULL;
    int best_node = -1, best_proc = -1;

    for (int node = 0; node < MAX_NODES; node++) {
        numa_proc_queue *npq = &sched->node_queues[node];
        spin_lock(&npq->lock);

        for (int proc = 0; proc < MAX_PROCS; proc++) {
            percpu_queue *q = &npq->queues[proc];
            io_item *head = atomic_load_explicit(&q->head, memory_order_acquire);

            if (!head) continue;

            // Fairness: don't dispatch same process too frequently
            uint64_t now = get_cycles();
            if (now - npq->last_dispatch[proc] < sched->throttle_threshold)
                continue;

            if (head->deadline < earliest) {
                earliest = head->deadline;
                best = head;
                best_node = node;
                best_proc = proc;
            }
        }
        spin_unlock(&npq->lock);
    }

    if (best) {
        sched->node_queues[best_node].last_dispatch[best_proc] = get_cycles();
    }
    return best;
}
```

### Test Plan for Bursty Workloads

1. **Microbenchmark**: Submit 10K-100K I/Os with deadlines (1ms, 5ms, 10ms, 50ms). Measure latency, track p50/p95/p99. Verify p99 < deadline.

2. **Burst test**: Submit 1000 I/Os in <10ms. Measure queue depth growth and tail latency. Compare against baseline.

3. **NUMA contention**: Run 8 processes on different NUMA nodes writing to shared NVMe. Measure cross-NUMA latency variance.

4. **Fairness test**: One process sends 90% of I/Os, another 10%. Verify minority gets <2x median latency of majority.

5. **Throttling validation**: Inject delays in dispatch path. Verify backpressure reaches submit path.

6. **Starvation test**: High-priority low-deadline stream + low-priority high-deadline stream. Verify low-priority completes within bounded time.

