A reusable barrier for N threads using the sense-reversing technique:

```c
#include <stdatomic.h>

typedef struct {
    atomic_int count;
    atomic_int sense;
    int N;
} barrier_t;

void barrier_init(barrier_t* b, int N) {
    b->N = N;
    atomic_init(&b->count, 0);
    atomic_init(&b->sense, 0);
}

void barrier_wait(barrier_t* b) {
    int local_sense = atomic_load_explicit(&b->sense, memory_order_acquire) ^ 1;

    if (atomic_fetch_add(&b->count, 1, memory_order_acq_rel) == b->N - 1) {
        atomic_store_explicit(&b->sense, local_sense, memory_order_release);
        atomic_store(&b->count, 0);
    } else {
        while (atomic_load_explicit(&b->sense, memory_order_acquire) != local_sense) {
            // spin-wait; atomically yields to scheduler on some platforms
        }
    }
}
```

**How it works:**
1. Each thread computes a local sense (opposite of current global sense)
2. Thread atomically increments count; last arrival (when count reaches N) resets count and flips global sense via release
3. Other threads spin-wait until global sense matches their local sense

**Reuse:** Global sense reversal naturally resets the barrier for the next cycle.

