Use a two-phase, sense-reversing barrier with a shared arrival counter and a global sense flag. Each thread maintains a local sense bit initialized to false. On `barrier_wait()`, a thread atomically increments the arrival counter and checks if it is the last to arrive. If so, it resets the counter and toggles the global sense flag, signaling all waiting threads to proceed. All other threads spin on the global sense until it matches their local sense, then flip their local sense and continue. This alternation allows the barrier to be reused across multiple rounds without reinitialization.

Minimal sketch:

```c
struct barrier {
    atomic_int arrival_count;
    bool sense;
    int num_threads;
};

void barrier_init(struct barrier *b, int n) {
    atomic_init(&b->arrival_count, 0);
    b->sense = false;
    b->num_threads = n;
}

void barrier_wait(struct barrier *b) {
    bool my_sense = !b->sense;
    int position = atomic_fetch_add(&b->arrival_count, 1) + 1;
    if (position == b->num_threads) {
        atomic_store_explicit(&b->arrival_count, 0, memory_order_release);
        b->sense = my_sense;
    } else {
        while (b->sense != my_sense) {
            // spin
        }
    }
}
```

**Memory ordering on x86 vs ARM:**

On **x86 (TSO)**, the store buffer and implicit ordering mean that a release store in the last thread synchronizes with subsequent loads. The `atomic_fetch_add` uses acquire semantics by default, ensuring the thread sees all prior writes. No explicit memory fences are required for correctness due to strong hardware ordering, though `atomic_thread_fence` may be used for clarity.

On **ARM (weak ordering)**, memory ordering is not guaranteed by default. The release store must be explicitly used to ensure prior writes are visible before the signal, and the spinning loads must use acquire semantics to observe the updated sense. Without proper barriers, a thread could spin forever on a stale value. The `atomic_store_explicit(..., memory_order_release)` and the spinning load with acquire semantics provide the necessary synchronization on ARM.

