Implement per-device I/O credits with NUMA-aware local pools and a global limiter. In the ISR, atomically debit the device's credit; if exhausted, enqueue requests to a throttle queue and defer completion. Credit replenishment occurs on a per-timer tick from the local NUMA node to minimize cross-NUMA traffic. A global coordinator aggregates per-node load and enforces an upper bound on cross-NUMA traffic, preventing any single node from monopolizing shared fabric bandwidth. Credit bookkeeping is cgroup-aware: each cgroup carries its own credit budget sub-allocation, and requests are policed against both per-device and per-cgroup limits before entering the block layer. The fast path (credit available) completes in O(1) with a single atomic decrement; the slow path (throttled) re-queues with a backpressure signal to the scheduler, ensuring tasks yield appropriately while bounded latency guarantees are maintained.

Minimal C-like sketch:

```c
struct io_credit {
    atomic_t remaining;
    struct credit_pool *pool;
    struct cgroup *cg;
};

void isr_budget_debit(struct disk *disk, struct bio *bio) {
    struct io_credit *cr = per_cpu_ptr(disk->credits, smp_processor_id());

    if (atomic_dec_if_positive(&cr->remaining) < 0) {
        spin_lock(&disk->throttle_lock);
        list_add_tail(&bio->throttle_entry, &disk->throttle_q);
        spin_unlock(&disk->throttle_lock);
        raise_softirq(BLOCK_SOFTIRQ);
        return;
    }

    cgroup_budget_debit(bio->cg, 1);
    submit_bio(bio);
}
```

