## Why This Is Asked
Tests understanding of disk scheduling algorithms, end-to-end flow from I/O request to service, and practical data structure choices in kernel-like environments.

## Key Concepts
- **Elevator (SCAN) vs SSTF**: SCAN provides more uniform latency by serving all requests in sweep order, while SSTF can cause starvation for distant requests.
- **Direction management**: Track current direction and handle boundary reversal at min/max sector addresses.
- **Tie-breaking**: When multiple requests target the same sector, FIFO ordering by arrival time ensures fairness.
- **Fairness considerations**: SCAN inherently favors requests at disk edges but avoids starvation. For stronger fairness guarantees, C-SCAN (circular SCAN) provides equal service time per full sweep, or deadline-based schedulers can prioritize older requests.

## Code Example
```c
typedef struct Req {
    int sector;
    int arrival;
    int pid;
    struct Req* next;
} Req;

Req* enqueue(Req* head, Req* r, int dir) {
    // Insert sorted by sector; if equal, preserve arrival order
    if (!head || r->sector < head->sector || 
        (r->sector == head->sector && r->arrival < head->arrival)) {
        r->next = head;
        return r;
    }
    Req* cur = head;
    while (cur->next && (cur->next->sector < r->sector ||
        (cur->next->sector == r->sector && cur->next->arrival <= r->arrival)))
        cur = cur->next;
    r->next = cur->next;
    cur->next = r;
    return head;
}

Req* next_request(Req* head, int* dir, int minSector, int maxSector) {
    if (!head) return NULL;
    // Seek in current direction
    Req* best = NULL;
    Req** prev = &head;
    Req* cur = head;
    while (cur) {
        if ((*dir > 0 && cur->sector >= 0) || (*dir < 0 && cur->sector <= 0)) {
            if (!best) { best = cur; *prev = cur->next; break; }
        }
        prev = &cur->next;
        cur = cur->next;
    }
    // If no request in current direction, reverse and try again
    if (!best) { *dir = -*dir; return next_request(head, dir, minSector, maxSector); }
    return best;
}
```

