questions.answer:
Use an atomic counter `remain` initialized to N and a generation counter `gen`. When a thread calls `barrier_wait`, it atomically decrements `remain`. If the result is 0, this is the last thread: reset `remain` to N, increment `gen`, and wake all waiting threads. Otherwise, the thread spins (or waits via futex) on the generation counter until `gen` changes, naturally handling spurious wakeups by re-checking the condition in a loop.

```c
#include <stdatomic.h>

typedef struct {
    atomic_int remain;
    atomic_int gen;
    int N;
} barrier_t;

void barrier_init(barrier_t *b, int N) {
    atomic_init(&b->remain, N);
    atomic_init(&b->gen, 0);
    b->N = N;
}

void barrier_wait(barrier_t *b) {
    int my_gen = atomic_load_explicit(&b->gen, memory_order_acquire);
    int r = atomic_fetch_sub_explicit(&b->remain, 1, memory_order_acq_rel);
    if (r == 1) {
        atomic_store_explicit(&b->remain, b->N, memory_order_release);
        atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&b->gen, 1, memory_order_release);
    } else {
        while (atomic_load_explicit(&b->gen, memory_order_acquire) == my_gen) {
            // spin or futex_wait
        }
    }
}
```

**Timeouts**: Wrap the wait in a loop checking elapsed time; return a status (0 = success, ETIMEDOUT).

**Spurious wakeups**: The generation-based loop naturally handles these—the thread re-checks `gen` and continues waiting if no actual wakeup occurred.

