## MCS Lock Implementation for Per-CPU Queue

**What is an MCS Lock?**
A queue-based lock where each thread waits by spinning on its own flag in its own cache line, not on shared state. This eliminates false sharing and reduces cache bouncing.

**Interfaces**:
```c
void mcs_lock(struct mcs_node *n, volatile struct mcs_lock *lock);
void mcs_unlock(struct mcs_node *n, volatile struct mcs_lock *lock);
```

**Data Structures**:
```c
struct mcs_node {
    struct mcs_node *next;  // successor in queue
    int locked;             // 1 = wait, 0 = go
};

struct mcs_lock {
    struct mcs_node *tail;  // NULL when unlocked
};
```

**Lock Acquisition (mcs_lock)**:
```c
void mcs_lock(struct mcs_node *n, volatile struct mcs_lock *lock) {
    n->next = NULL;
    n->locked = 1;

    struct mcs_node *pred = __atomic_exchange_n(&lock->tail, n, __ATOMIC_ACQ_REL);

    if (pred != NULL) {
        smp_wmb();
        pred->next = n;

        while (n->locked == 1) {
            cpu_relax();
        }
    }
}
```

**Lock Release (mcs_unlock)**:
```c
void mcs_unlock(struct mcs_node *n, volatile struct mcs_lock *lock) {
    if (n->next == NULL) {
        if (__atomic_compare_exchange_n(&lock->tail, &n, NULL, 0, __ATOMIC_ACQ_REL, __ATOMIC_RELAXED)) {
            return;
        }
        while (n->next == NULL) {
            cpu_relax();
        }
    }
    smp_wmb();
    n->next->locked = 0;
}
```

**Enqueuing**: Thread atomically swaps itself into the tail using `__atomic_exchange_n`. The previous tail becomes its predecessor. The predecessor then links itself to the new node by setting `pred->next = n`.

**Per-Thread Spinning**: Each thread spins on its own `n->locked` flag in its own cache line. This avoids all CPUs racing on a single shared variable.

**Wake-up**: The lock holder sets `n->next->locked = 0`, directly waking only the successor. No broadcast needed.

**Why It Reduces Cache Bouncing**:
- Only the lock holder touches the shared `tail` pointer
- On release, only the successor's cache line gets invalidated (to clear `locked`)
- No broadcast invalidations to all CPUs—communication is 1-to-1
- Each node sits in a separate cache line (avoid false sharing)

**Testing Fairness**:
```c
void *bench_thread(void *arg) {
    ThreadData *td = (ThreadData *)arg;
    for (int i = 0; i < ITERATIONS; i++) {
        uint64_t start = rdtsc();
        mcs_lock(&td->node, &global_lock);
        uint64_t wait = rdtsc() - start;

        td->acquisitions++;
        td->total_wait += wait;
        td->max_wait = max(td->max_wait, wait);

        mcs_unlock(&td->node, &global_lock);
    }
    return NULL;
}

void run_fairness_test(int num_threads) {
    pthread_barrier_init(&barrier, NULL, num_threads);
    for (int i = 0; i < num_threads; i++) {
        pthread_create(&threads[i], NULL, bench_thread, &data[i]);
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < num_threads; i++) {
        pthread_join(threads[i], NULL);
    }

    printf("Fairness metrics:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < num_threads; i++) {
        printf("Thread %d: %d acquisitions, avg_wait=%.2f, max_wait=%lu\n",
               i, data[i].acquisitions, 
               (double)data[i].total_wait / data[i].acquisitions,
               data[i].max_wait);
    }
}
```

**Key Implementation Notes**:
- Use `__attribute__((aligned(64)))` to align nodes to cache line boundaries
- `smp_wmb()` ensures proper ordering before unlocking the successor
- `cpu_relax()` yields CPU to reduce contention during spin
- The outer if in unlock handles the case where a new waiter arrives between checking `n->next` and setting `tail` to NULL

**Gotchas**:
- Nodes must be cache-line-aligned to prevent false sharing
- Use proper memory barriers (`smp_wmb()`, `mb()`)
- Disable interrupts during critical sections if in kernel context

